INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2243,2,'2013-04-13 15:50:44','2013-04-13 19:50:44','<h1>Do you experience “handbag syndrome”?</h1>\nBig purses have been the trend over the last several years, but we see the trend moving to smaller, lighter bags, which is a relief to those who are experiencing shoulder and neck pains due to heavy handbags--also known as “handbag syndrome.”\n\nBig purses can be convenient, but there is a down side. It’s easy to keep adding the items like water bottles, cameras, wet wipes, and hair clips, without ever emptying them out when you don’t need them to lighten the load on your neck, shoulders and back.\n\nA heavy handbag, shoulder bag, or purse can injure the neck, back and shoulders. The neck has a natural curve that evenly distributes forces on the spine. This means that if you carry a heavy bag on one shoulder over a long period of time, this natural curve starts to get distorted and can lead to chronic neck and shoulder pains, back pain, and even headaches.\n\nMake sure to clean out your purse frequently and store unused credit cards, pill bottles, receipts, makeup, keys and change at home. Or, better yet, switch to a smaller bag and just carry the essentials, such as a small mirror, lipstick, small brush, purse, pen, car key, house key, &amp; mobile phone. You can always slip the small bag into your bigger tote for commuting or travel.','Do you experience “handbag syndrome”?','','inherit','closed','closed','','2241-autosave','','','2013-04-13 15:50:44','2013-04-13 19:50:44','',2241,'http://www.westcoast-east.com/2241-autosave/',0,'revision','',0);
